		<div  class="comment even thread-even depth-1 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/2a7240907dc893d6f7726e1704c5e751?s=45&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D45&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn">Chimi Changga</cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://www.cybersalon.org/cypherpunk/#comment-1909">	September 17, 2013 at 5:41 am</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>The question &#8220;&#8230; how can we apply Bitcoin to ethical markets rather than black markets?&#8221; presupposes that black-markets are inherently unethical. The truth is that black-markets (aka System D, shadow, informal and underground economies) only exist because governments attempt to restrict the natural rights of their citizens by protecting markets of special interests from competition, raise unassailable barriers of entry to mainstream economies  to poor entrepreneurs, engage in theft through re-distributive taxation, assume people do not own their bodies and therefore have no right to determine what to put in them, etc. Black-markets only exist when public markets are not freed. They are therefore an ethical response to unethical government behavior.</p>
<p>Black-markets, excluding explicitly criminal activities as illicit drugs, prostitution, etc., are already (in composite) the world&#8217;s 2nd largest economy employing half the world&#8217;s people. By 2012 its predicted by the OECD to employ 2/3 of the world&#8217;s workers . So, if you think people in the bitcoin community should focus on the mainstream economies and shun black-markets then you have ostracized most of world&#8217;s population.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="reply"><a class='comment-reply-link' href='/cypherpunk/?replytocom=1909#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-1909", "1909", "respond", "851")'>Reply</a></div><!-- .reply -->
		</div><!-- #comment-##  -->

	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li id="comment-2004">
		<div  class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/b5e898739fd7313389b150ffa1feb3d9?s=45&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D45&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn"><a href='http://www.richardboase.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Richard Boase</a></cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://www.cybersalon.org/cypherpunk/#comment-2004">	September 21, 2013 at 2:47 pm</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>Chimi,<br />
You raise excellent points, and you&#8217;re absolutely right, I have made that implicit assumption that black markets are inherently unethical.<br />
It&#8217;s no secret however that Bitcoin has a bit of a &#8216;PR&#8217; problem. People distrust it precisely because it can be used for illicit purposes, and by extension, illicit immoral purposes, not just naughty ones.<br />
I&#8217;m slightly perplexed by the idea that &#8216;the Black Market economy is the second largest economy&#8217; as every light casts shadows, this would seem to make perfect sense, but what&#8217;s the third largest economy in this spectrum of economies, or the fourth? </p>
<p>There are grey markets, markets which we can legitimately understand as markets for things which fall into neither ethical or unethical categories, and most of those things are down to selective perception i.e. what you deem acceptable or unacceptable according to the context and culture in which you live. </p>
<p>My point, is that that higher, noble goals should be the priority, rather than using the technology as a direct route to selfish enrichment. One thing we&#8217;ve learned about payment ecosystems particularly is that there has to be a certain amount of &#8216;give and take&#8217;, that hoarders can and will eventually destroy every value-based exchange ecosystem by monopolising it&#8217;s substantive commodity. Gold, Petrol&#8230; Bitcoin, etc. </p>
<p>That&#8217;s why recontextualising bitcoin as a tool to balance the scales is so important&#8230; but I agree with you wholeheartedly, your comments are very astute and bear a great deal of consideration. It&#8217;s those who&#8217;re sold into slavery, and who dwell in poverty without happiness and in deep pain who&#8217;re  most at risk and in need. </p>
<p>How can we use bitcoin to even the odds for everyone?</p>
			</div>
