	<li id="comment-2078">
		<div  class="comment even thread-even depth-1 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/f64f1b76c2123ea4d7b30ed69acc6391?s=45&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D45&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn">Steven Schear</cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://www.cybersalon.org/cypherpunk/#comment-2078">	September 23, 2013 at 10:16 pm</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>Bitcoin only has a PR problem because the shills and toadies of government issued money have made it their business to discredit it. The same thing happened to almost every attempt of unregulated private money to compete with fiat (e.g., e-gold, Liberty Dollars, Liberty Reserve). Any journalist or academic that mentions Bitcoin&#8217;s actually minor unsavory side without also mentioning that USD and Euros (and all other fiat) are routinely used for illicit drug purchases, murders for hire, prostitution, illegal gambling, etc. is not to be trusted.</p>
<p>Currency can&#8217;t support empathy any more than it can have a morality (Jon Matonis, <a href="https://twitter.com/jonmatonis/status/381000449727279104" rel="nofollow">https://twitter.com/jonmatonis/status/381000449727279104</a>). One person&#8217;s gray-market is another&#8217;s black-market. Best not to try to accomplish these things with technology as it has always ended badly (e.g., a lack of financial freedom except for government and the elites). Noble goals are best left as the sole province of individual and social decisions.</p>
<p>Bitcoin (and its highly probable follow-ons, Bitcoin 2, Open Transactions, etc.) will better the odds for everyone by helping leveling the playing field for all.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="reply"><a class='comment-reply-link' href='/cypherpunk/?replytocom=2078#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-2078", "2078", "respond", "851")'>Reply</a></div><!-- .reply -->
		</div><!-- #comment-##  -->

	<ul class="children">
	<li id="comment-2180">
		<div  class="comment odd alt depth-2 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/b5e898739fd7313389b150ffa1feb3d9?s=45&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D45&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn"><a href='http://www.richardboase.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Richard Boase</a></cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://www.cybersalon.org/cypherpunk/#comment-2180">	September 26, 2013 at 1:10 pm</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>&#8220;Bitcoin only has a PR problem because the shills and toadies of government issued money have made it their business to discredit it.&#8221;</p>
<p>I think this is a very biased way of looking at the situation. If the article above demonstrates anything it&#8217;s that the invention is antithetical to big government and government issued money, but I have read very few critiscisms of bitcoin from &#8216;the Establishment&#8217; other than Paul Krugman&#8217;s famous dismissal of it. </p>
<p>I think generally the community nexus of socially inclined economists would say that a deflationary currency is unworkable and/or undesirable, and I would tend to agree with them up until the point where the elasticity of the bitcoin system is spread to thinly that deflation slows to 1% a year&#8230; at which point it may well become a viable &#8216;currency&#8217; rather than what it is at the moment, a sort of tech stock cum commodity item.</p>
<p>As for supporting moral or noble causes&#8230; I believe that by design bitcoin supports lightweight infrastructure changes for those at the bottom of the economic pile, and I believe it&#8217;s an &#8216;enlightened&#8217; version of money in that it&#8217;s philosophy is global, inclusive and unregulated by traditional power structures. Much as I admire Jon Matonis&#8217; writings, and agree that a technology in itself can&#8217;t be moral or immoral (rather only it&#8217;s uses can) this article finishes with an appeal to look for the ways in which we can use Bitcoin in ethical and empowering ways.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="reply"><a class='comment-reply-link' href='/cypherpunk/?replytocom=2180#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-2180", "2180", "respond", "851")'>Reply</a></div><!-- .reply -->
		</div><!-- #comment-##  -->

	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li id="comment-5471">
